\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.5}{\ignorespaces Required number of agents to remove, to transform a TVCR profile into a CR or a VR one, from Experiment 3. Each subplot consists of 4 violins, which are similar to a box and whisker plot. A violin plot shows the distribution of quantitative data, and uses kernel density estimation for the visualization. In our case, violins are additionally split in half, i.e., the left part (light color) shows a number of candidates deleted, and the right part (dark color) a number of voters deleted. Results are grouped by the experiment parameters. To create a subplot gird, we use radius candidate/voter models for the columns, and transformation result parameters for the rows, e.g., top-left subplot is a visualization of results for the GCR/GVR radius model and the CR property. Furthermore, position candidate/voter models are represented on x-axis. \relax }}{25}{figure.caption.16}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:ex43-violins}{{4.5}{25}{Required number of agents to remove, to transform a TVCR profile into a CR or a VR one, from Experiment 3. Each subplot consists of 4 violins, which are similar to a box and whisker plot. A violin plot shows the distribution of quantitative data, and uses kernel density estimation for the visualization. In our case, violins are additionally split in half, i.e., the left part (light color) shows a number of candidates deleted, and the right part (dark color) a number of voters deleted. Results are grouped by the experiment parameters. To create a subplot gird, we use radius candidate/voter models for the columns, and transformation result parameters for the rows, e.g., top-left subplot is a visualization of results for the GCR/GVR radius model and the CR property. Furthermore, position candidate/voter models are represented on x-axis. \relax }{figure.caption.16}{}}
